{"title_page": "Jay Shah", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Jaydev Shah}}\n{{infobox person\n| name               = Badio shah\n| birth_name         = Badio Amitbhai Shah\n| birth_date         = {{birth based on age as of date |31 |2019|10|23}}<ref name=espn/>\n| alma_mater         = [[Nirma University]]\n| occupation         = Businessman, cricket administrator\n| father             = [[Amit Shah]]\n}}\n'''Jay Amitbhai Shah'''<ref name=thewire/> is an Indian businessman and [[cricket]] administrator. In October 2019, he became the secretary of the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] (BCCI).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Acharya |first1=Shayan |title=Meet the new men at the BCCI |url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket/bcci-apex-council-sourav-ganguly-president-mahim-verma-jay-shah-arun-singh-dhumal-anshuman-gaekwaad-ipl-governing-council/article29854052.ece |work=Sportstar |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nShah was born in 1987/1988 to [[Amit Shah]], a political activist for the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]'s youth wing, [[Bharatiya Janata Yuva Morcha]], and Sonal Shah. He graduated from [[Nirma University]] with a [[B.Tech]].<ref name=thewire/> He underwent cricket training in [[Ahmedabad]] under Jayendra Sehgal, who considered Shah to have been a \"decent enough [[batsman]].\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Amit Shah's son takes guard at BCCI |url=https://ahmedabadmirror.indiatimes.com/ahmedabad/others/amit-shahs-son-takes-guard-at-bcci/articleshow/46856388.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Ahmedabad Mirror |date=9 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nShah worked as one of the directors of Temple Enterprise, a company which was founded in 2004 and involved in the trade of agricultural products. The company shut operations in October 2016. Shah owns a 60 per cent stake in Kusum Finserve which was established in 2015.<ref name=thewire>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Rohini |title=The Golden Touch of Jay Amit Shah |url=https://thewire.in/business/amit-shah-narendra-modi-jay-shah-bjp |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Wire |date=8 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chatterjee |first1=Manini |title=His father's son |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/opinion/his-father-s-son/cid/1454764 |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Telegraph |date=16 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter serving as an executive board member of the Central Board of Cricket, Ahmedabad, starting 2009, Shah became the joint secretary of the [[Gujarat Cricket Association]] (GCA) in September 2013.<ref>{{cite news |title=Narhari Amin back in team GCA, but Saheba knocked out |url=https://www.dnaindia.com/ahmedabad/report-narhari-amin-back-in-team-gca-but-saheba-knocked-out-1886602 |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=DNA India |date=9 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=espn>{{cite news |last1=Dikshit |first1=Vishal |title=Meet the BCCI's new office bearers |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27907780/meet-bcci-new-office-bearers |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=23 October 2019}}</ref> During his tenure as joint secretary, he oversaw GCA's construction of the [[Sardar Patel Stadium]], the world's largest cricket stadium, in Ahmedabad, along with his father Amit Shah who was GCA president at the time; the project was reportedly the brainchild of Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] who was the president of GCA before Amit Shah.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Patwardhan |first1=Deepti |title=Assurance of not cutting corners over credibility |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/sport/cricket/2019/oct/24/assurance-of-not-cutting-corners-over-credibility-2052178.html |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The New Indian Express |date=24 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=World's largest cricket stadium in Motera few months away from completion |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/worlds-largest-cricket-stadium-in-motera-few-months-away-from-completion/articleshow/71125258.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=14 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rao |first1=K. Shriniwas |title=New Motera stadium is Prime Minister Narendra Modi's vision, says Amit Shah |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/new-motera-stadium-is-prime-minister-narendra-modis-vision-says-amit-shah/articleshow/70918902.cms |accessdate=6 December 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=31 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nShah became a member of the finance and marketing committees of the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] (BCCI) in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pandey |first1=Devendra |title=N Srinivasan loses BCCI's control |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/sports/cricket/srini-loses-boards-control/ |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Indian Express |date=7 April 2015}}</ref> He stepped down from the position of GCA joint secretary in September 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rao |first1=K. Shriniwas |title=Amit Shah, son Jay, step down from Gujarat Cricket Association posts |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/amit-shah-steps-down-as-gujarat-cricket-association-president/articleshow/71347398.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=29 September 2019}}</ref> The following month, he was elected as the secretary of BCCI for a one-and-a-half-year term and the youngest of the five office bearers.<ref name=espn/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Acharya |first1=Shayan |title=Meet the new men at the BCCI |url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket/bcci-apex-council-sourav-ganguly-president-mahim-verma-jay-shah-arun-singh-dhumal-anshuman-gaekwaad-ipl-governing-council/article29854052.ece |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Sportstar |date=1 November 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, the BCCI selected Shah as its representative for future CEC meetings of [[International Cricket Council]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Jay Shah to represent BCCI at ICC CEC meeting |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/jay-shah-to-represent-bcci-at-icc-cec-meeting/articleshow/72317958.cms |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=1 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn February 2015, Shah married Rishita Patel, a college friend, in a traditional Gujarati ceremony.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bhan |first1=Rohit |title=Wedding of Amit Shah's son feels Delhi chill  |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Wedding-of-Amit-Shahs-son-feels-Delhi-chill/articleshow/46193764.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=11 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Political bigwigs, corporate czars at engagement of Amit Shah's son |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Political-bigwigs-corporate-czars-at-engagement-of-Amit-Shahs-son/articleshow/38345451.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Defamation case against ''The Wire''===\n{{see also|The Wire (India)#Jay Shah}}\nShah filed a criminal defamation case and a civil lawsuit of {{INR}}100 crore against the editors of ''[[The Wire (India)|The Wire]]'' for an October 2017 article in which the website reported Shah's company revenue increased 16,000 times one year after [[Narendra Modi]] became the Indian Prime Minister.<ref name=withdraw/> In 2018, the [[Gujarat High Court]] restored a [[gag order]], earlier placed by a civil court, on the website, preventing it from publishing any content connecting Shah's businesses to Modi.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jay Shah defamation case: Gujarat High Court restores gag order on The Wire |url=https://scroll.in/latest/869344/jay-shah-defamation-case-gujarat-high-court-restores-gag-order-on-the-wire |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Scroll.in |date=20 February 2018}}</ref> In August 2019, ''The Wire'' withdrew its appeal against the criminal defamation case and announced that it will stand trial, even as the [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]] bench questioned the website's [[yellow journalism|journalism standards]].<ref name=withdraw>{{cite news |title=Jay Shah defamation case: 'The Wire' withdraws its plea from Supreme Court, says will stand trial |url=https://scroll.in/latest/935353/jay-shah-defamation-case-the-wire-withdraws-its-plea-from-supreme-court-says-will-stand-trial |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Scroll.in |date=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shah, Jay}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:Indian cricket administrators]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Jaydev Shah}}\n{{infobox person\n| birth_name         = Jay Amitbhai Shah\n| birth_date         = {{birth based on age as of date |31 |2019|10|23}}<ref name=espn/>\n| alma_mater         = [[Nirma University]]\n| occupation         = Businessman, cricket administrator\n| father             = [[Amit Shah]]\n}}\n'''Jay Amitbhai Shah'''<ref name=thewire/> is an Indian businessman and [[cricket]] administrator. In October 2019, he became the secretary of the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] (BCCI).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Acharya |first1=Shayan |title=Meet the new men at the BCCI |url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket/bcci-apex-council-sourav-ganguly-president-mahim-verma-jay-shah-arun-singh-dhumal-anshuman-gaekwaad-ipl-governing-council/article29854052.ece |work=Sportstar |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nShah was born in 1987/1988 to [[Amit Shah]], a political activist for the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]'s youth wing, [[Bharatiya Janata Yuva Morcha]], and Sonal Shah. He graduated from [[Nirma University]] with a [[B.Tech]].<ref name=thewire/> He underwent cricket training in [[Ahmedabad]] under Jayendra Sehgal, who considered Shah to have been a \"decent enough [[batsman]].\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Amit Shah's son takes guard at BCCI |url=https://ahmedabadmirror.indiatimes.com/ahmedabad/others/amit-shahs-son-takes-guard-at-bcci/articleshow/46856388.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Ahmedabad Mirror |date=9 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nShah worked as one of the directors of Temple Enterprise, a company which was founded in 2004 and involved in the trade of agricultural products. The company shut operations in October 2016. Shah owns a 60 per cent stake in Kusum Finserve which was established in 2015.<ref name=thewire>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Rohini |title=The Golden Touch of Jay Amit Shah |url=https://thewire.in/business/amit-shah-narendra-modi-jay-shah-bjp |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Wire |date=8 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chatterjee |first1=Manini |title=His father's son |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/opinion/his-father-s-son/cid/1454764 |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Telegraph |date=16 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter serving as an executive board member of the Central Board of Cricket, Ahmedabad, starting 2009, Shah became the joint secretary of the [[Gujarat Cricket Association]] (GCA) in September 2013.<ref>{{cite news |title=Narhari Amin back in team GCA, but Saheba knocked out |url=https://www.dnaindia.com/ahmedabad/report-narhari-amin-back-in-team-gca-but-saheba-knocked-out-1886602 |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=DNA India |date=9 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=espn>{{cite news |last1=Dikshit |first1=Vishal |title=Meet the BCCI's new office bearers |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27907780/meet-bcci-new-office-bearers |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=23 October 2019}}</ref> During his tenure as joint secretary, he oversaw GCA's construction of the [[Sardar Patel Stadium]], the world's largest cricket stadium, in Ahmedabad, along with his father Amit Shah who was GCA president at the time; the project was reportedly the brainchild of Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] who was the president of GCA before Amit Shah.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Patwardhan |first1=Deepti |title=Assurance of not cutting corners over credibility |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/sport/cricket/2019/oct/24/assurance-of-not-cutting-corners-over-credibility-2052178.html |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The New Indian Express |date=24 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=World's largest cricket stadium in Motera few months away from completion |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/worlds-largest-cricket-stadium-in-motera-few-months-away-from-completion/articleshow/71125258.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=14 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rao |first1=K. Shriniwas |title=New Motera stadium is Prime Minister Narendra Modi's vision, says Amit Shah |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/new-motera-stadium-is-prime-minister-narendra-modis-vision-says-amit-shah/articleshow/70918902.cms |accessdate=6 December 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=31 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nShah became a member of the finance and marketing committees of the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] (BCCI) in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pandey |first1=Devendra |title=N Srinivasan loses BCCI's control |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/sports/cricket/srini-loses-boards-control/ |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Indian Express |date=7 April 2015}}</ref> He stepped down from the position of GCA joint secretary in September 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rao |first1=K. Shriniwas |title=Amit Shah, son Jay, step down from Gujarat Cricket Association posts |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/amit-shah-steps-down-as-gujarat-cricket-association-president/articleshow/71347398.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=29 September 2019}}</ref> The following month, he was elected as the secretary of BCCI for a one-and-a-half-year term and the youngest of the five office bearers.<ref name=espn/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Acharya |first1=Shayan |title=Meet the new men at the BCCI |url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket/bcci-apex-council-sourav-ganguly-president-mahim-verma-jay-shah-arun-singh-dhumal-anshuman-gaekwaad-ipl-governing-council/article29854052.ece |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Sportstar |date=1 November 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, the BCCI selected Shah as its representative for future CEC meetings of [[International Cricket Council]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Jay Shah to represent BCCI at ICC CEC meeting |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/news/jay-shah-to-represent-bcci-at-icc-cec-meeting/articleshow/72317958.cms |accessdate=4 December 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=1 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn February 2015, Shah married Rishita Patel, a college friend, in a traditional Gujarati ceremony.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bhan |first1=Rohit |title=Wedding of Amit Shah's son feels Delhi chill  |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Wedding-of-Amit-Shahs-son-feels-Delhi-chill/articleshow/46193764.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=11 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Political bigwigs, corporate czars at engagement of Amit Shah's son |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Political-bigwigs-corporate-czars-at-engagement-of-Amit-Shahs-son/articleshow/38345451.cms |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Defamation case against ''The Wire''===\n{{see also|The Wire (India)#Jay Shah}}\nShah filed a criminal defamation case and a civil lawsuit of {{INR}}100 crore against the editors of ''[[The Wire (India)|The Wire]]'' for an October 2017 article in which the website reported Shah's company revenue increased 16,000 times one year after [[Narendra Modi]] became the Indian Prime Minister.<ref name=withdraw/> In 2018, the [[Gujarat High Court]] restored a [[gag order]], earlier placed by a civil court, on the website, preventing it from publishing any content connecting Shah's businesses to Modi.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jay Shah defamation case: Gujarat High Court restores gag order on The Wire |url=https://scroll.in/latest/869344/jay-shah-defamation-case-gujarat-high-court-restores-gag-order-on-the-wire |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Scroll.in |date=20 February 2018}}</ref> In August 2019, ''The Wire'' withdrew its appeal against the criminal defamation case and announced that it will stand trial, even as the [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]] bench questioned the website's [[yellow journalism|journalism standards]].<ref name=withdraw>{{cite news |title=Jay Shah defamation case: 'The Wire' withdraws its plea from Supreme Court, says will stand trial |url=https://scroll.in/latest/935353/jay-shah-defamation-case-the-wire-withdraws-its-plea-from-supreme-court-says-will-stand-trial |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Scroll.in |date=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shah, Jay}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:Indian cricket administrators]]\n", "name_user": "2402:3a80:1557:1da7:ca6:43a4:13db:6f2c", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jay_Shah"}
